<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Counter Pakistan's Charges on Kashmir </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0402133194 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1230 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0402133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] India has charged Pakistan with adopting a 
conscious policy of ethnic cleansing of religious minorities. 
In a hard hitting statement in Geneva, the finance minister, 
Dr. Manmohan Singh said discrimination against the minorities is 
in-built in Pakistan's Constitution. Terming Islamabad's record 
on human rights as abysmal, he observed that Pakistan's 
championship of the cause of Kashmiris lacks credibility. Dr. 
Manmohan Singh said Pakistan continues to remain in illegal 
occupation of one-third of Jammu and Kashmir in flagrant 
violation of UN resolutions. The finance minister reaffirmed 
India's commitment to peace and stability in the region. It is 
in this spirit, he said, that New Delhi made six proposals, 
including a draft agreement on peace and tranquility along the 
Line of Control. 
  The Congress-I says Jammu and Kashmir cannot revert back to 
the 1953 status. The party spokesman, Mr. Chandulal 
Chandrarkar, told reporters in New Delhi today that the clock 
cannot be put back. He said the accession of Jammu and Kashmir 
to India is final and irreversible. 
  The BJP [Bharatiya Janata Party] leader, Mr. Atal Behari 
Vajpayee, has welcomed the prime minister's suggestion to freeze 
the Kashmir issue for the time being and to hold talks with 
Pakistan to improve relations. Talking to newspersons in 
Lucknow today, he said Pakistani propaganda against India should 
be countered effectively. Mr. Vajpayee said the people in the 
Kashmir valley are fed up with terrorist activities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

