<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Kuwait </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trial Postponed Until 5 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0502112094 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 1039 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuwait, 5 Feb (KUNA) -- The State Security Court 
here today has postponed hearings in the case of the terrorist 
network which attempted to assassinate former U.S. President 
George Bush during his visit to Kuwait last year instigated and 
planned by the Iraqi intelligence until 5 March. 
  The reason for the postponement was to brief lawyers about 
the case before the hearing. 
  The court met under the chairmanship of Judge Salah al-Fahd 
and listened to the witness Abd al-Hamid al-Shatti, a Kuwaiti 
national who works at the Ministry of Interior. The witness 
said that when one of the accused was arrested he confessed that 
he was trained by Iraqi intelligence to assassinate Bush and 
blow up vital and crowded Kuwaiti locations. 
  He stressed that after the investigations and interrogations 
it became clear that Iraqi intelligence had provided the two 
main suspects: Wali al-Ghazali and Salim Nasir, with what was 
needed, referring to their confession that they were Iraqi 
intelligence personnel. 

</TEXT>

