<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Complete Strike' Held in Soldarity With Kashmir </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0502160094 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0502160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The nation today observed complete strike to 
express solidarity with brethren in occupied Kashmir facing 
unprecedented rein of repression unleashed by Indian occupation 
forces. People on both sides of the Line of Control dividing 
the Kashmir valley also observed complete strike. 
  In occupied Kashmir, the All Parties Hurriat Conference 
decided to observe the strike in response to an appeal made by 
Prime Minister Ms. Benazir Bhutto. Today was a closed day. 
Business and commercial centers, government and semi-government 
offices, and educational institutions remained closed. Public 
transport remained off the road and life came to a standstill 
throughout the country. 
  The call for strike to express solidarity with the Kashmiri 
people struggling for their right of self-determination was 
given by the Special Committee of the National Assembly on 
Kashmir. The government of Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto gave 
all-out support to the strike, highlighting the nation's 
commitment to the Kashmiri cause. Opposition parties joined 
hands, demonstrating that the entire nation is united behind the 
government on this national issue. 
  In the twin cities of Rawalpindi and Islamabad, processions 
were taken out and rallies organized by people of all shades of 
political opinion, business, traders, students and labor 
organizations to express solidarity with the people of Kashmir. 
The processionists parading through various streets chanted 
slogans against repression the Indian Army and paramilitary 
forces have unleashed against the people in occupied Kashmir. 
  Addressing the rally, speakers condemned the Indian 
atrocities in occupied Kashmir and demanded that the United 
Nations implement its resolutions on Kashmir in order to 
determine the wishes of the Kashmiri people in a free and 
impartial plebiscite. They said the unprecedented unity shown 
by the people throughout the country today spoke of their 
determination to continue to extend moral and political support 
to their Kashmiri brethren in their struggle against Indian 
hegemony. They condemned the Indian president for his unsavory 
comments against Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, and said Ms. 
Benazir Bhutto has emerged as the spokesman of the Kashmiri 
people. 
  Later, leaders of the rally went to the Indian High 
Commission and handed over a memorandum. 
  Trade and labor organizations also staged demonstrations in 
the twin cities of Rawalpindi and Islamabad to express 
solidarity with their Kashmiri brethren. Carrying banners and 
placards, the marchers condemned Indian atrocities and urged the 
world community to halt human rights abuses in the held valley. 
They supported the government policy on Kashmir and assured 
that they will not rest until the Kashmiri people throw off 
their Indian yoke. [passage omitted] 
  Supporting the call of the Pakistani prime minister, a 
complete strike was observed in occupied Kashmir. Reports say 
life remained paralyzed in towns and cities of the valley. All 
government and private institutes and offices; schools, 
colleges, and universities; banks; and courts remained closed 
and transport was off the road. Agency reports say Kashmiris 
staged demonstration rallies in the capital, Srinagar, and other 
big towns of the valley. They were chanting slogans against 
Indian troops' atrocities. Indian soldiers used brute force 
against the demonstrators. The All Parties Hurriat Conference 
and various religious and mojahedin organizations have endorsed 
the call for today's strike to demonstrate that the people of 
occupied Kashmir wholeheartedly appreciate Pakistan's stand on 
Kashmir. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

