<H3> <TI>   Roundup of 4-7 Feb Clashes in Southern Region </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hizballah Kills 3 Israelis, Wounds 3 </H4>
<F P=102> NC0702121594 Paris AFP in English 1153 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0702121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Marj 'Uyun, Lebanon, Feb 7 (AFP)--Hizballah 
guerrillas killed three Israeli soldiers and wounded three 
others in south Lebanon on Monday, triggering retaliatory air 
strikes, security sources said. 
  The ambush took place as an Israeli patrol drove along a 
road 
in Israel's self-declared "security zone" in south Lebanon, the 
sources said. 
  The attack was claimed by the pro-Iranian Hizballah. 
  Shortly afterwards Israeli warplanes raided Hizballah 
positions near the south Lebanon port city of Sidon, the sources 
said. 
  [In an earlier, related report, Paris AFP in English at 1135 
GMT on 7 February, stated the following: "Guerrillas attacked 
an Israeli army patrol with anti-tank rockets and automatic 
weapons on Monday wounding six soldiers, security sources in 
south Lebanon said. 
  ["The ambush took place as the patrol drove along a road in 
Israel's self-declared "security zone" in south Lebanon, the 
sources said. 
  ["A spokesman for the Islamic Resistance, the armed wing of 
the Hizballah movement, told AFP in Beirut that its guerrillas 
destroyed an Israeli Merkava tank, killing or wounding an 
unspecified number of Israeli soldiers. 
  ["Two other bomb attacks on patrols from the Israeli army 
and 
its proxy South Lebanon Army militia (SLA) caused no casualties. 
  ["Guerrillas also fired 10 Katyusha rockets on the outskirts 
of Marj 'Uyun, where Israeli forces and the SLA have their south 
Lebanon headquarters, but nobody was hurt, the SLA said. 
  ["Hizballah and the pro-Syrian Amal movement carry out 
frequent raids against Israeli forces in south Lebanon. 
  ["The pace slowed down ahead of the January 16 Geneva summit 
between Syrian President Hafiz al-Asad and US President Bill 
Clinton, but there have been around 20 attacks since."] 

</TEXT>

