<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Rejects Proposal for Talks Without 'Arafat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0702053494 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 0500 GMT 7 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0702053494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Israel has decided not to send its peace 
delegation, with Shim'on Peres at its head, to Cairo today if 
Yasir 'Arafat does not participate in the talks. According to 
Qol Yisra'el's diplomatic correspondent, this was decided last 
night in a meeting between Prime Minister Rabin and Foreign 
Minister Peres. More from reporter Dick Winter: 
  [Begin recording] [Winter] [passage omitted] The prime 
minister is not playing the PLO's game. Last night, in his 
meeting with the Arab Israeli Dr. Ahmad al-Tibi, who has been 
described by Palestinian watchers as the PLO's ambassador to 
Israel, Prime Minister Rabin rejected the PLO's proposal to hold 
the talks today without 'Arafat being present. 
  Rabin is keeping Israel's next moves close to the chest. In 
a speech last night welcoming Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus 
to Israel, the prime minister repeated the stand he has been 
taking for the last month: 
  [Rabin] Mr. Prime Minister, in our quest for peace we have 
learned that we must stand our ground on matters of life and 
death, to guarantee our security, and not to run after false 
solutions. For us, peace without security is not peace. We are 
mindful of lessons from your distant and not so distant past. 
One of them is taken from your tragic history: the agreement 
which abandoned your country to the destructive jaws of the Nazi 
regime. We have learned to rely only on ourselves. 
  [Winter] This morning, Prime Minister Rabin will again meet 
with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres, as well as the entire 
Israeli delegation and with senior members of the defense 
establishment, to decide on Israel's next move. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

