<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres Interviewed on `Difficulties' in Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0602180394 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1605 GMT 6 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0602180394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres by political </F>
correspondent Shlomo Raz at the Prime Minister's Office in 
Jerusalem -- live] 
  [Text] [Raz] Mr. Foreign Minister, are you going to Cairo 
tomorrow? 
  [Peres] I hope so. We still have to clarify a few things. 
  [Raz] Where do the contacts with the PLO stand? Is there 
any chance of concluding matters in the present round of talks? 
  [Peres] Israel has prepared a complete agreement. Now we 
have to also reach agreement with the PLO. 
  [Raz] Will 'Arafat arrive tomorrow? 
  [Peres] I cannot answer for him. 
  [Raz] Mr. Peres, where do the major obstacles lie? 
  [Peres] In the complexity of the situation on the ground, in 
the various scenarios, concerns, fears, and aspirations. 
Whoever thinks we are negotiating over where a policeman should 
stand or not is simply deluding himself. These negotiations are 
about the crux of the matter, about peoples' emotions, fears, 
and hopes. The fact that this is expressed in arguments about 
the stationing of this or that policeman merely serves to 
highlight the difficulties in bridging the existing gaps between 
the Palestinian and Israeli positions. 
  [Raz] Mr. Peres, do you really think that the IDF [Israel 
Defense Forces] is throwing a monkey wrench into the works, as 
one newspaper headline stated? 
  [Peres] No one ever heard me make such a statement or use 
such a remark in the course of the past week. Many of the 
things attributed to me are mere assumptions based on groundless 
psychological analyses. 
  [Raz] Do you have any reservations with the IDF's degree of 
involvement in the current stage of the process? 
  [Peres] I think it is important that the IDF be involved. 
The negotiations definitely have their security and military 
aspects and I have no complaints about the IDF's involvement. 
  [Raz] Thank you Mr. Peres. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

