<H3> <TI>   Iranian `Rebels' Conclude `War Games' Near Border </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0702130394 Paris AFP in English 1233 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0702130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, Feb 7 (AFP)--Thousands of Iranian rebels 
using helicopters, tanks, heavy artillery and anti-aircraft guns 
on Monday ended four days of war games in an Iraqi region near 
the border with Iran, a rebel spokesman said. 
  Women rebels for the first time piloted helicopters that 
carried troops to mock battlefields during the first manoevers 
of the year, said Farid Soleymani, spokesman for Iran's main 
armed opposition group, the People's Mojahedin 
  The Mojahedin has several military bases in Iraq, near the 
border with Iran. 
  The announcement of the exercise, codenamed "Iran's hope," 
the first to he held since October 1993, came one day after 
Iraqi opposition fighters paraded in Iran, near the border with 
Iraq. 
  The Mojahedin on Sunday meanwhile called on Iranians to join 
protests that took place last week and revolt against the 
government of President 'Ali Akbar Hashemi-Rafsanjani. 
  Clashes occurred in the southern Iranian city of Zahedan 
last 
Tuesday. The Mojahedin claimed that protests had also taken 
place in other southern cities. 
  Baghdad and Tehran, who harbour each other's opposition 
groups, often accuse each other of interfering in their internal 
affairs. 

</TEXT>

