<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jordan's Decision Part of `U.S. Effort' To Isolate Iran </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0402162894 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 4 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0402162894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Unusual Calm in Iran's Response to </F>
Jordan's Expulsion of Diplomats"] 
  [Text] Tehran, London, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT--Iran yesterday 
responded in an unusually calm manner to Jordan's decision to 
expel 21 Iranian diplomats. A spokesman for the Foreign 
Ministry in Tehran said that "Jordan's decision has come to our 
attention and we are going to implement it." 
  Diplomatic sources have said that the decision to expel the 
diplomats was taken at "the highest level." And that King 
Husayn during his visit to Washington received "comprehensive 
documents" about what were termed subversive activities carried 
out by 26 Iranian diplomats in Amman. The sources pointed out 
that other "intelligence information" from the United States and 
Israel reveals the Iranian Embassy's implication in "activities 
harmful to Jordanian interests." 
  Iranian sources say that Jordan's decision is part of a 
broader "U.S. effort" to isolate Iran. And that Washington 
asked two other Arab states, namely Oman and Qatar, to 
reconsider their policies toward Iran. But the diplomatic 
sources said that Iran is accused of involvement in the 
following actions: 
--Distributing huge quantities of propagandist informational 
items in Jordan. These items are sometimes transported by 
trucks. 
  --Financing "suspect candidates" in the November elections. 
  --Trying to cause a split and instigate opposition to 
Jordan's position on the peace process in the Middle East. 
  --Financing radical groups to oppose the peace process. 
  --Encouraging certain terrorist operations like the attack 
on cinemas in Amman and al-Zarqa'. 
  --Iran's possible involvement--via Hizballah--in the 
assassination of a Jordanian diplomat in Beirut. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

