<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bhutto on Kashmir Strike, Indian Leader's Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0602123894 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network in Urdu 0200 
GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0602123894 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Urdu </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Ms. Benazir Bhutto has expressed 
happiness over yesterday's successful strike and said that it 
has provided a new inspiration and strength to the valiant 
struggle of the Kashmiri people. In a message last night, she 
said that observance of the strike from the coastal regions of 
Karachi and Gwadar to the blood-soaked Anantnag in occupied 
Kashmir was aimed as a reminder of the Kashmiris' basic right 
and to assert that the Kashmiris are not alone in their just 
struggle. She expressed confidence that the strike will force 
world public opinion to realize once again that it will not be 
in the interests of the world community to ignore the issue of 
Jammu and Kashmir. 
  Referring to the struggle of the Kashmiri people, the prime 
minister said that the strike was a part of the government's 
policy to get the Kashmir issue resolved in accordance with UN 
resolutions. She said that this was the strategy under which she 
traveled to Geneva to address the UN Human Rights Commission 
where she raised the Kashmir issue. Ms. Benazir Bhutto said 
that the strike and her address to the UN Human Rights 
Commission have helped highlight the Kashmir issue at the global 
level. She said that the peaceful proposals presented by 
Pakistan in accordance with international law are responded to 
with threats of war. We cannot be browbeaten by these threats, 
she added. 
  The prime minister said that some Indian leaders have 
started 
criticizing her personal life. She does not care for this 
criticism because she prefers the Kashmiris' right to 
self-determination over anything else, she added. Prime 
Minister Ms. Benazir Bhutto said that all such activities point 
to India's bewilderment. She said that we still favor a 
peaceful solution of the Kashmir issue and believe that peace 
cannot be achieved without providing justice. The prime minister 
said that Pakistan still wishes India to hold talks to resolve 
the Kashmir issue. She urged India to take steps to peacefully 
resolve the Kashmir problem in accordance with international law. 
  Prime Minister Bhutto said Pakistan will continue to extend 
diplomatic, moral, and political support to the Kashmiri 
brethren until India holds talks with Pakistan. She said that 
by showing solidarity with the Kashmiris, Pakistan has proven 
that Pakistanis and Kashmiris have the same soul. She said that 
world public opinion has started taking note of Indian brutal 
atrocities in occupied Kashmir. Indian propaganda that the 
freedom struggle in Kashmir depends on Pakistan has been 
exposed, she added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

