<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Various Sectors React to Attack on Mosque </TI></H3>
<H4>   Interior Minister Comments </H4>
<F P=102> EA0702201594 Khartoum SUNA in Arabic 1715 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> EA0702201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Khartoum SUNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Khartoum, 7 Feb (SUNA) -- The interior minister, 
Brigadier 'Abd-al-Rahim Muhammad Husayn, has denied that a 
foreign country was behind the incident at al-Thawrah mosque 
last Friday [4 February] in which 16 people were killed and 20 
others wounded. He pointed out that investigations were 
continuing to find out more about this mystery, particularly as 
one of the criminals was still being treated and could not be 
questioned because of the current state of his health. 
  In a statement he delivered today at the Transitional 
National Assembly, the minister reviewed the incident at 
al-Thawrah mosque and the criminal acts carried out by an armed 
group of foreigners. He said that their moves began with an 
attack on a police station at Umm Baddah north where they 
claimed that they wanted to make a report but then seized 
weapons [passage omitted] 
  In response to questions and requests for clarifications, 
the 
minister said that notwithstanding the basic principles of 
general policy there must be measures for control and regulation 
of the procedures relating to arrivals in the country. He 
expressed the hope that further investigations would provide 
more information about this mysterious incident. He ruled out 
that the criminals were targeting Usamah Bin Ladin, proprietor 
of the Hijrah company working on the al-Tahaddi road. 

</TEXT>

