<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Various Sectors React to Attack on Mosque </TI></H3>
<H4>   Origins of 3 Gunmen Identified </H4>
<F P=102> PM0802125094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 7 Feb 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM0802125094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ['Uthman Mirghani report: "Khartoum Rules Out Foreign </F>
Financing; Opposition Accuses Front and `Afghans'"] 
  [Excerpts] London, Khartoum, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Sudanese 
Interior Minister Brigadier General 'Abd-al-Rahim Muhammad 
Husayn yesterday ruled out the existence of any foreign 
financing for the armed group that carried out the mosque 
massacre. Meanwhile Sudanese opposition sources have said that 
the gunmen, two of whom were killed and a third wounded, are 
"Arab Afghans" [Arabs who fought alongside Afghan mojahedin 
against Soviet forces]. [passage omitted] 
  Mubarak al-Mahdi, official in charge of external action in 
the opposition Ummah Party and former interior minister, has 
said that the mosque incident was carried out by a Sudanese 
group whose members' features indicate that they are either from 
western or southern Sudan, according to the testimonies of some 
eyewitnesses. They were wearing Sudanese costumes. Their faces 
were veiled. [passage omitted] 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT yesterday, Mubarak 
al-Mahdi said yesterday that the al-Riyadh district incident 
differs from the Shaykh Abu-Zayd Mosque incident. It can be 
said that the former (the al-Riyadh incident) is linked to a 
process of settling accounts and disputes within the "Arab 
Afghans" groups present in Sudan, which are armed. 
  He said that linking the al-Riyadh incident group and the 
al-Thawrah incident group "is an attempt to conceal the 
operation carried out by security services to terrorize citizens 
and oppositionists, especially as mosques have become platforms 
for the opposition." 
  He added that "the government is responsible for the two 
incidents, because it allowed these elements to enter Sudan. 
And its attempt to lay the responsibility on foreigners is 
unacceptable. It opened the door to foreigners, the Arab 
Afghans, and others, granting residence, citizenship, and the 
right to carry firearms." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

