<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Czech Premier Meets Weizman, Likud Chairman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702182394 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1300 
GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702182394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus had a short 
meeting with Israeli President Ezer Weizman in Jerusalem today. 
But before the meeting with the Israeli president, he [Klaus] 
had talks with Binyamin Netanyahu, chairman of the right-wing 
opposition Likud bloc, who is a staunch opponent of the present 
Israeli Government's policy on Palestinians. 
  Talks between President Weizman and Vaclav Klaus centered 
mainly on the general situation in the Middle East while Klaus' 
discussions with Binyamin Netanyahu concentrated on the level of 
privatization in both countries and on economic reform in the 
Czech Republic. 
  Prime Minister Klaus commented to Czech radio on his talks 
[with Netanyahu]. 
  [Begin Klaus recording] This is a political party that puts 
emphasis on similar principles as the political party [Civic 
Democratic Party], which I lead, and [on similar principles] as 
the government coalition that rules in the Czech Republic. We, 
therefore, preferred to talk about our views on civic, social, 
political, and economic matters. The Middle East issue or the 
question of Palestine did not dominate our discussions. [passage 
omitted] It is absolutely evident that the Czech Republic is, 
in these areas [of privatization], the country with a greater 
private sector, the country with a lesser tax burden, the 
country with less regulatory measures and state intervention in 
the economy. These were matters the Israeli party was 
exceedingly interested in. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

