<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak, Musa Mediate PLO-Israeli Talks in Cairo </TI></H3>
<H4>   Musa, Peres Discuss Progress </H4>
<F P=102> NC0802143194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1215 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0802143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 8 Feb (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa met 
today with Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres and discussed 
the progress achieved so far in eliminating the obstacles 
hindering the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho agreement. 
  The meeting was attended on the Egyptian side by Ambassador 
to Israel Mahmud Basyuni and Foreign Ministry spokesman 
Ambassador Naji al-Ghatrifi and on the Israeli side by 
Environment Minister Yosi Sarid and Ambassador David Sultan. 
  Musa met earlier today for one hour with Palestinian 
President Yasir 'Arafat. 
  'Arafat, Peres, and Musa are expected to get together at a 
working luncheon Musa is hosting for the Palestinian and Israeli 
delegations. 
  In another development, Avi Gil, Israeli Foreign Ministry 
deputy director general, stated that at noon today President 
Husni Mubarak contacted Shim'on Peres. The Israeli foreign 
minister informed Mubarak of the real stand regarding the 
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations so far, Gil said. 
  He added that President Mubarak invited Peres to attend a 
meeting with him at 1830 this evening. 
  The spokesman noted that the Israeli minister will also meet 
with the Austrian president at 1930 today. 
  In other developments, sources close to the 
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations stated to MENA that the general 
atmosphere of the talks is good. 
  The Palestinian delegation sources said that the Palestinian 
and Israeli negotiators will continue their negotiations today 
and tomorrow. Peres will not leave Cairo until late on 
Wednesday evening or early Thursday morning after finding a 
solution to the obstacles to signing the agreement. 
  The same sources clarified that the minutes of the 
negotiations, including all the points of difference and 
agreement, will only be initialed by the two sides. The points 
of difference will be left for President 'Arafat and Yitzhaq 
Rabin to resolve later. 
  The sources said that the points of difference revolve 
basically around the issue of the crossings and Israel's 
insistence on maintaining its security control over them. 
  The news agency has also learned that the paper being 
discussed currently is the Davos document, which is based on the 
Cairo paper. The Davos document consists of three main pages in 
addition to a special and a separate eight-page section on the 
minutes regarding the crossings. 
  The Israelis made some changes to the Davos document which 
the Palestinians reject, insisting that this matter should be 
seen as a comprehensive deal that includes the Davos and Cairo 
documents. 
  It is worth noting here that the Palestinian delegation to 
the talks includes Ahmad Quray', alias Abu-'Ala', Nabil Sha'th, 
Akram Haniyah, and Faysal al-Husayni; the Israeli delegation 
includes Uri Savir, Foreign Ministry director general; Yo'el 
Zinger, the legal advisor to the Foreign Ministry; and Uzi 
Dayan, chief of military planning. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

