<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak, Musa Mediate PLO-Israeli Talks in Cairo </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sources: `Differences Still Persist' </H4>
<F P=102> NC0902070994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0620 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0902070994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 9 Feb (MENA)-- The Palestinian-Israeli 
negotiations continued up to dawn today under the cochairmanship 
of Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres and the presence of Foreign Minister 'Amr 
Musa, in an attempt to reach an agreement that would eliminate 
the obstacles hindering the implementation of the 
Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of Principles. Sources close to 
the negotiations have said that the stances assumed by both 
sides have not changed a bit and that differences still persist 
on the crossing points and the area of Jericho. 
  [Paris AFP in English at 0210 GMT on 9 February carries a 
Cairo-datelined item by Haro Chakmakjian on the negotiations, 
which adds: "Israeli and PLO negotiators made `some progress' in 
a marathon session of talks deep into the night aimed at 
launching Palestinian self-rule, but an accord would still need 
more work, Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres said here 
early Wednesday. 
  ["`We made some progress and we shall try tomorrow 
(Wednesday) to complete our work,' Peres told reporters after 
more than four hours of discussions with a PLO delegation led by 
Chairman Yasir 'Arafat. 
  ["Peres said both sides would meet again at about 10:00 a.m. 
(0800 GMT) Wednesday, and he would meet 'Arafat at about midday. 
  ["`We are working on a text that we are to agree on,' Peres 
added. 
  ["Another Israeli negotiator, Foreign Ministry Director 
General Uri Savir, said differences with the PLO had been 
reduced, but `nobody at this point knows how close we are' to an 
agreement. 
  ["The points of disagreement were sensitive, he explained. 
`We haven't set a deadline yet.' 
  ["Negotiators from the Palestine Liberation Organisation 
could not be reached for comment on Tuesday's talks held at the 
Andalus Palace in the northeastern suburb of Heliopolis, where 
'Arafat was staying. 
  ["Savir said both sides were working `word by word and 
paragraph by paragraph.' 
  ["They were concentrating on security issues such as the 
control of international borders and road access to Jewish 
settlements, which, together with the size of the autonomous 
Jericho area, have been the main stumbling blocks. 
  ["Earlier Egyptian leaders stepped in to try to break the 
deadlock after an inconclusive round of talks Monday."] 
  The same AFP report adds: ["An Egyptian Foreign Ministry 
official told AFP Egypt had `made every effort to enable the two 
sides to reach an accord.' 
  ["President Husni Mubarak held a 45-minute meeting with 
'Arafat and Peres, after a day when the two sides reported no 
progress. 
  ["Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa later met Peres for an hour to 
try to resolve the remaining difficulties. 
  ["Peres said he had the `mandate of the government' and 
would 
stay on in Cairo as long as necessary to overcome obstacles. 
The points agreed in Davos still stood, he said, denying 
Palestinian charges that Israel was backing out. 
  ["However, he told Israeli radio: `Even if we sign an 
agreement on security issues, which are on the agenda, there is 
a range of other subjects which we have not yet tackled and 
which will have to be settled.' 
  ["They included the powers to be devolved to the Palestinian 
autonomy council, the electoral system and the transfer of 
civilian authority."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

