<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak, Musa Mediate PLO-Israeli Talks in Cairo </TI></H3>
<H4>   Israeli Envoy on `Climate of Optimism' </H4>
<F P=102> NC0902123294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1140 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0902123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 9 Feb (MENA)--Egyptian sources today said 
that the Palestinian and Israeli sides have made progress in 
their talks over the past two days, particularly with regard to 
the remaining problems facing the implementation of the 
Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of Principles. 
  The sources said that the two delegations will continue 
their 
meetings today to examine points of disagreement concerning the 
crossings and the Jericho area. The sources said that the 
outcome of the Palestinian-Israeli talks is expected to be 
announced tonight or tomorrow. 
  Israel's Ambassador to Cairo David Sultan said the talks 
have 
made progress. He voiced the hope that more progress will follow 
and that the remaining points of disagreement will be settled. 
The Israeli ambassador said the talks will continue today and 
that there is a climate of optimism. The ambassador pointed to 
a need to reach agreement on particular issues but added that 
others have been settled in talks over the past two days. The 
Israeli ambassador declined to elaborate further, saying that 
the talks are still under way and that it is better to wait 
until they are over before discussing their details. 

</TEXT>

