<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Comments on Cause of `Political Crisis' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0902065194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2225 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0902065194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 8 Feb (MENA)--Yemeni Foreign Minister 
Muhammad Salim Basindwah has attributed the cause of the current 
political crisis in his country to the rivalry for power, which 
has affected the flow of foreign investment into Yemen. He 
denied that the worsening crisis can be blamed on external 
factors. 
  In statements to AL-AHRAM published Wednesday, he noted that 
charges that his country is providing refuge for terrorists 
might be prompted by some Afghan Arabs' infiltration of Yemen. 
He said that their infiltration takes place secretly and 
without the security authorities' consent. 
  He pointed out that Yemen has managed to normalize its 
relations with some of the Gulf Cooperation Council member 
countries and is still pursuing normalization with other 
countries so that these ties will return to their level 
preceding the crisis of the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
  He called for not using the new oil oil discoveries in his 
country as pretext for contemplating partition, otherwise its 
wealth will turn into a misfortune instead of a blessing. 
  He said that clouds still loom Arab-Iraqi ties and that 
further strenuous efforts and essential amendments to the Arab 
League charter are needed. 
  On Yemen's stand on the Middle East market, the Yemeni 
foreign minister said his country is not inclined to end the 
boycott of Israel before a comprehensive and just peace is 
established in the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

