<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mordekhay: Northern Border `Relatively Quiet' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0902113494 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1000 GMT 9 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0902113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The commander of the Northern Command has said that 
the northern border is relatively quiet. There is constant 
activity along the border by both Israel and the terrorist 
elements, in particular Hizballah, he said. Major General 
Yitzhaq Mordekhay said the IDF [Israel Defense Forces] is 
operating inside the security zone and outside it according to 
the policy decided on by the political echelon. He noted that 
the understandings with Syria worked out in the wake of 
Operation Accountability are still in effect. The Israeli side 
of the northern border is not being shelled. 
  It is difficult to act against Hizballah when its members 
operate in built-up areas populated by civilians, he said. Gen. 
Mordekhay said that the IDF is carrying out initiated actions 
because were it not doing so, the situation on the ground would 
be worse. The general added that the IDF has drawn lessons from 
Monday's [7 February] firefight in the al-Rayhan area in which 
four soldiers were killed. Gen. Mordekhay made these remarks 
to our army affairs correspondent, Karmela Menashe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

