<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Barak Antimissile Missile Testing `Successful' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0802145994 Tel Aviv DAVAR in Hebrew 8 Feb 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> TA0802145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv DAVAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by On Levi] </F>
  [Text] The testing phase of antimissile missile Barak have 
been completed, and the Israeli Navy will procure its first 
Barak system in the coming months. 
  "Baraqi completed a three-part series of tests at the end of 
last year, and all three tests were successful." This was 
revealed yesterday by a senior Israeli Navy figure. He added 
that the Navy plans to install this missile system on the Saar 5 
missile boats which are being built in the United States, and on 
some of the Saar 4.5 vessels. 
  The Barak missile is the result of a joint REFA'EL [Armament 
Development Authority] and IAI [Israel Aircraft Industries] 
development. The missile's range is about 10 km, and it can hit 
a pinpointed target. The missile will be mounted on Saar 5 and 
Saar 4.5 as the central defense weapon system. The senior 
figure said that Barak is the best missile of its kind in the 
world, and its uniqueness lies in its ability to intercept 
low-flying missiles cruising a few meters above water. The 
missile can be also used against attacking aircraft. 
  In the last three tests, the missile was fired from a naval 
platform, and it intercepted a Gabriel ship-to-ship missile. In 
one of the tests, Barak hit Gabriel as it had been programmed, 
while in the other two tests, it passed a short distance from it 
-- also in accordance with the programming which sought to 
collect data about the missile's performance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

