<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Aircraft Violations Protested to UN </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0802135094 Baghdad INA in Arabic 1015 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN0802135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New York, 8 Feb (INA) -- Iraq has informed the UN 
General Secretariat of U.S. aircraft violations of its airspace 
on provocation and reconnaissance missions. The aircraft, 
breaking the sound barrier, are also dropping hostile leaflets 
and flares. 
  In a letter to UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali, 
Iraq's permanent UN representative said between 21-31 January, 
the U.S. aircraft violated Iraq's airspace, conducting 719 
sorties over wide areas in northern and southern Iraq. 
  He pointed out that a red drone was seen in the Umm Qasr 
region, heading from west to east. Another drone, coming from 
Saudi Arabia, dropped leaflets between al-Shu'aybah and 
al-Wahdah Airport. 
  He also confirmed that on 25 January, a drone was observed 
heading toward al-Dayr region. On 27 January, another drone was 
seen falling in the al-Barjasiyah region. 
  Iraq's permanent UN representative added that two 
reconnaissance TR-1 planes were detected over al-Basrah, 
al-'Amarah, al-Nasiriyah, al-Diwaniyah, and southern al-Najaf, 
which then headed for Saudi territories. 
  He added that on 28 January, a drone violated Iraq's 
airspace 
over al-Basrah, Safwan, al-Shu'aybah, Jabal Sinam, and returned 
to Kuwait again on the same day. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

