<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Debt Rescheduling Agreement Signed With Japan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0702074494 Amman JORDAN TIMES in English 7 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> JN0702074494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman JORDAN TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Amman (J.T.)--Japan and Jordan Sunday [6 February] 
signed an agreement rescheduling over $14 million in Jordan's 
debts owed to Japan. 
  The agreement, signed by Finance Minister Sami Qammuh and 
Japanese Ambassador Yuji Ikeda, followed a decision in June by 
the Paris Club of major government creditors to ease Jordan's 
foreign debts. 
  Under the accord, Japan will reschedule installments on 
arrears from July 1993 until February 1994, the Jordan News 
Agency, Petra, said. The sum will be added to a previously 
rescheduled amount of $87.3 million dollars, it added. 
  The deal provides for a grace period of nine years for 
government debts and seven years for government-guaranteed 
commercial loans. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

